{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "A friendly look at how machines find patterns, make predictions, generate ideas, and assist people—and why the choices behind AI matter.",
    "title": "Artificial Intelligence in Everyday Life"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Artificial intelligence is a set of methods that lets computers recognize patterns, make decisions, or produce useful output from data and instructions. It powers systems as different as photo search, translation, and game-playing programs.",
      "title": "What Artificial Intelligence Helps Computers Do"
    },
    {
      "description": "Most modern AI improves by finding regularities in examples: many labeled photos, past purchases, spoken phrases, or medical measurements. The same pattern-finding idea can suggest a song, flag fraud, or predict traffic.",
      "title": "How Artificial Intelligence Finds Patterns in Data"
    },
    {
      "description": "Generative AI can create text, images, music, code, and other content by predicting plausible continuations from patterns it has seen. Its output can be impressive, but plausible words or pictures are not automatically accurate or fair.",
      "title": "Why Generative Artificial Intelligence Can Create—and Mislead"
    },
    {
      "description": "AI shapes ordinary choices in maps, feeds, customer support, accessibility tools, factories, hospitals, and scientific research. Its effects depend not only on an algorithm, but also on the data, goals, and people using it.",
      "title": "Where Artificial Intelligence Shows Up in Daily Decisions"
    },
    {
      "description": "AI work brings together software developers, data analysts, designers, domain experts, researchers, policy makers, and people who test systems for safety and bias. Meaningful projects range from helping farmers monitor crops to helping doctors organize information.",
      "title": "People and Projects Behind Responsible Artificial Intelligence"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "A Biologia olha para a vida em todas as escalas: das moléculas dentro de uma célula às florestas, epidemias e espécies que compartilham o planeta. Ela ajuda a explicar por que herdamos características, como o corpo se defende e como nossas escolhas afetam os seres vivos ao redor.",
    "title": "Biologia: a ciência da vida em ação"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Biologia não é só decorar nomes de animais e partes do corpo. É investigar como os seres vivos obtêm energia, crescem, se reproduzem, percebem o ambiente e mantêm a vida funcionando.",
      "title": "O que a Biologia pergunta sobre os seres vivos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Uma célula é pequena demais para ser vista a olho nu, mas já consegue organizar materiais, usar energia, responder a sinais e produzir novas células. Todos os organismos dependem desse tipo de organização.",
      "title": "Como as células sustentam toda a vida"
    },
    {
      "description": "O DNA guarda instruções que influenciam características herdadas, como grupos sanguíneos e parte da aparência. Ao mesmo tempo, ambiente e experiências também participam da história de cada organismo.",
      "title": "Como o DNA liga gerações de seres vivos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Alimentação, sono, vacinas, micróbios e qualidade da água têm Biologia por trás. Conhecer o corpo e os organismos ao redor ajuda a interpretar informações de saúde sem cair facilmente em mitos.",
      "title": "Biologia no corpo, na saúde e no cotidiano"
    },
    {
      "description": "Biólogos podem monitorar animais, analisar surtos de doenças, trabalhar com conservação, alimentos, genética, laboratórios, ensino ou biotecnologia. Perguntas como “por que espécies desaparecem?” e “como uma doença se espalha?” viram investigação e ação.",
      "title": "Onde a Biologia atua: saúde, ambiente e tecnologia"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Quantum mechanics describes how matter and light behave at atomic and subatomic scales. Its rules can feel strange—particles can act like waves, outcomes are probabilistic—but they power lasers, computer chips, medical scanners, and emerging quantum technologies.",
    "title": "Quantum Mechanics: The Rules Beneath Everyday Matter"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "At the scale of atoms, familiar objects give way to electrons, photons, and other tiny systems. Quantum mechanics gives remarkably accurate rules for predicting what these systems can do and what measurements can reveal.",
      "title": "What Quantum Mechanics Describes: Atoms, Light, and Tiny Systems"
    },
    {
      "description": "An electron can produce interference like a wave yet arrive at a detector as a single event. This wave-particle behavior is not a metaphor; it is one of the central clues that nature does not follow everyday intuition at small scales.",
      "title": "Why Quantum Particles Behave Like Waves and Particles"
    },
    {
      "description": "Quantum theory often predicts probabilities rather than one certain outcome. That uncertainty is built into the theory, while the probabilities themselves can be tested with astonishing precision.",
      "title": "How Quantum Mechanics Predicts Chances, Not Certainties"
    },
    {
      "description": "The quantum behavior of electrons helps explain chemical bonds, the colors of materials, and why solids can conduct or resist electricity. Transistors, LEDs, solar cells, and lasers all rely on these microscopic rules.",
      "title": "Quantum Mechanics Inside Phones, Light Bulbs, and Solar Panels"
    },
    {
      "description": "Physicists, engineers, chemists, materials scientists, and software researchers use quantum ideas in laboratories and technology teams. Their work ranges from designing new materials and sensors to studying quantum computing and the structure of the universe.",
      "title": "Who Uses Quantum Mechanics and What They Build"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Civil Procedure is the rulebook for moving a lawsuit through court: who may sue, where a case belongs, how parties exchange evidence, and how disputes end. These rules shape whether a claim is heard fairly, efficiently, and at all.",
    "title": "How Civil Lawsuits Move Through Court"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Civil Procedure governs the process rather than the underlying dispute. Whether the case involves a broken contract, an injury, discrimination, or a business conflict, procedure sets the steps that give each side notice and a meaningful chance to be heard.",
      "title": "Civil Procedure: The Rules Behind a Civil Lawsuit"
    },
    {
      "description": "A lawsuit begins with practical gatekeeping questions: Which court has authority over the people and dispute? Is the location proper? Can this plaintiff bring this claim? The answers can determine where—or whether—the case proceeds.",
      "title": "Why Court Authority and Location Matter in Civil Procedure"
    },
    {
      "description": "Most civil cases turn on information held by the opposing side. Discovery is the structured process for requesting documents, asking written questions, taking sworn testimony, and narrowing disputes before trial.",
      "title": "How Discovery Reveals Evidence Before Trial"
    },
    {
      "description": "Civil Procedure balances two competing needs: parties deserve a fair opportunity to present their case, while courts must prevent delay, surprise, and needless expense. Deadlines, motions, and judicial case management are tools for that balance.",
      "title": "How Civil Procedure Balances Fairness, Time, and Cost"
    },
    {
      "description": "Civil procedure matters far beyond televised trials. Lawyers use it to protect clients, judges use it to manage crowded dockets, and businesses, advocates, and public-interest groups use it to bring or defend claims. Questions about class actions, settlements, jury trials, and appeals all begin with procedural choices.",
      "title": "How Civil Procedure Shapes Real Disputes and Legal Work"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "El urbanismo estudia cómo se organizan las ciudades: calles, viviendas, parques, transporte y servicios. Ayuda a entender por qué unos lugares invitan a caminar y convivir, mientras otros dificultan la vida diaria, y cómo las decisiones sobre el espacio afectan la salud, la economía y el clima.",
    "title": "La ciudad como espacio para vivir juntos"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "El urbanismo observa la ciudad como un sistema de lugares y conexiones. No se trata solo de edificios: una banqueta, una ruta de autobús, una plaza o la distancia a una escuela pueden cambiar cómo transcurre el día de miles de personas.",
      "title": "Qué organiza el urbanismo en una ciudad"
    },
    {
      "description": "Una calle puede servir para circular, comprar, esperar, jugar, encontrarse o descansar. Su ancho, sus árboles, sus cruces y la velocidad de los autos determinan si se siente segura, activa y agradable para quienes la usan.",
      "title": "Cómo las calles urbanas cambian la vida cotidiana"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cuando viviendas, empleos, tiendas, escuelas y transporte quedan muy separados, las personas dependen de trayectos largos. El urbanismo busca acercar oportunidades y facilitar opciones como caminar, usar bicicleta o transporte público.",
      "title": "Distancias, transporte y acceso a oportunidades"
    },
    {
      "description": "Los parques, la sombra y los árboles no son adornos urbanos. Reducen el calor, absorben agua de lluvia, ofrecen espacio para convivir y pueden hacer que un barrio sea más saludable y resistente ante cambios climáticos.",
      "title": "Por qué el espacio público y el verde importan en urbanismo"
    },
    {
      "description": "Urbanistas trabajan con comunidades, gobiernos, arquitectos, ingenieros, geógrafos y especialistas ambientales. Pueden diseñar planes de barrio, analizar datos de movilidad, mejorar cruces peligrosos, proteger patrimonio o impulsar vivienda más accesible.",
      "title": "Quiénes toman decisiones sobre la ciudad"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "L’histoire de l’art observe comment les images, les bâtiments et les objets racontent leur époque. Des fresques aux installations contemporaines, elle relie formes, matériaux, croyances, pouvoir et vies quotidiennes.",
    "title": "L’art comme miroir et moteur des sociétés"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Une œuvre n’est pas seulement « belle » ou « étrange » : elle a été faite par quelqu’un, pour un lieu, un public et souvent un usage précis. Un portrait peut afficher un statut, un temple organiser une croyance, une affiche chercher à convaincre.",
      "title": "Ce que l’histoire de l’art lit dans une œuvre"
    },
    {
      "description": "La lumière, la couleur, l’échelle, le geste et le cadrage orientent notre regard. Quelques choix visuels peuvent faire paraître un souverain puissant, une scène intime, ou un événement ordinaire profondément dramatique.",
      "title": "Comment les artistes guident le regard"
    },
    {
      "description": "Peintures, statues, textiles, photographies, affiches, jeux vidéo et architecture façonnent la mémoire collective. Les images peuvent célébrer, protester, transmettre des récits ou faire discuter une société de ce qu’elle veut montrer.",
      "title": "Quand les images influencent la culture et le pouvoir"
    },
    {
      "description": "Conserver une sculpture, préparer une exposition, écrire sur une œuvre, concevoir une affiche ou étudier un monument : l’histoire de l’art nourrit des métiers de musées, de patrimoine, d’édition, de création et de médiation culturelle.",
      "title": "Les métiers et lieux de l’histoire de l’art"
    },
    {
      "description": "Pourquoi certaines œuvres deviennent-elles célèbres ? Qui décide de ce qui entre dans un musée ? Que révèle un matériau venu de loin sur le commerce et la colonisation ? Ces questions transforment une visite de galerie en enquête sur le monde.",
      "title": "Les grandes questions posées par l’histoire de l’art"
    }
  ]
}
